column11: Note: this is a probability question, asking for the top finisher, not a delegate share question! Pledged delegates are those delegates whose votes are determined by the outcome of the primaries (Bustle). Comparison Classes Inform Probability Estimates. Instead of only looking at the inside view — qualities of the candidates and case at hand — I am also going to look at forecasters who have a successful track record of predicting Super Tuesday outcomes in the past, with different candidates. I identified one such candidate as David Rothschild, an economist at Microsoft Research, who leads a research project called PredictWise which aggregates data from various betting and forecasting sources. He estimates that in 10 of the 11 states, Trump is up — ranging from 67% to 96%. This leads me to a 75% estimate in favor of Trump having the most pledged delegates. The other 25%, I will allocate 15% to Ted Cruz, and 10% to Marco Rubio.

Donald Trump goes into the Super Tuesday contests with a 82-17-16 delegate lead over Cruz, followed by Rubio. Most Super Tuesday primary states award delegates proportionally, and with polling showing Trump up by double digits in most states, these large margins could completely shut out third place showings by Cruz or Rubio, while he would pick up delegates even in states he loses. Trump and Cruz are competing for the same evangelical voters, so even a Cruz win in Texas, which would deprive Rubio of any delegates from that state, combined with strong wins for Trump in Alabama and across the South, similar to his South Carolina margin, would significantly raise his delegate edge. (C: compare to margins of victory in early primary states; H: Tuesday polling estimates from 538, P: post-mortem analysis from early state predictions, N: norms and protocols for delegate apportionment)

Besides Texas and Arkansas, the most recent polls indicate that Trump has a lead in every Super Tuesday state. Coupled with his 82 current delegates vs. 17 for Cruz and 16 for Rubio, there would have to be a drastic swing in voter sentiment within the next day in order for Trump not to have the most pledged candidates. Additionally, the G.O.P. altered its delegate allocation rules following the messy primary of 2012, meaning that Trump will likely receive 1/3 of the delegates in states which he does not win (as he will be the second-place finisher in those contests). It appears that such a reform in the delegate allocations will come back to haunt the Republican establishment, which despises Trump.

Populate vote numbers & actual delegate votes are two separate shoes. The difference b/w the two enhances uncertainty through the entire election process with last minute delegate deals usually part of this process; something impossible to forecast.

The number of delegates available to be won state-by-state is known. Who will win how many in each state is unknown. The situation is complicated because the GOP made changes to the primary format since the last presidential race. Essentially, it was thought that if a Republican nomination got wrapped up too quickly, while a Democratic race continued, the Republicans would be shut out of the news cycle. To counteract this possibility, the early state contests were designed to be proportional, rather than winner-take-all, making it difficult for anyone to walk away with it early. So my methodology for this question involves going through the contests state by state to make an estimate of delegate accumulation for each of the candidates. I take the known number of delegates available and apply the latest polling data to make the calculations. Admittedly, this is where things get squishy. In some states like Colorado, the polling is not recent. And of course, I acknowledge the inherent problems of polling in today's world where many people do not have land lines and will not answer polls. You can take the data and run the numbers numerous times with various tweaks and assumptions. At the end of all this I estimate that Trump will end up with 43% of the delegates, Cruz will get 32% and Rubio will get 24% by the closure date. The other candidates will be out of it.

At the moment, Trump has 17 pledged delegates, Cruz has 11, Rubio has 10, Kasich has 5, Bush has 4 and Carson has 3. A further 727 pledged delegates are up for grabs before or on Super Tuesday. A rough analysis of current polling in the 16 states holding Republican primaries on or before March 1, 2016 show Trump holding a lead in at least seven states, including major states like Georgia, Tennessee, and South Carolina. National poll numbers also continue to show at least a ten point spread between Trump and his nearest competitor, Ted Cruz. Unless Cruz begins to really surge or the establishment coalesces around a single candidate, it seems highly likely that Trump will have the most pledged delegates by the end of the Super Tuesday primaries.

Donald Trump winning New Hampshire easily means that he won't lose support; Ted Cruz will win support from the more ideological and evangelical voters while the Establishment will divide themselves fairly evenly with Jeb Bush's organization gaining him the most votes. Marco Rubio and Ben Carson will be seen as not ready enough to be President. John Kasich doesn't have enough of an established organization in states other than New Hampshire or Ohio to get a lot of support but his solid second place in New Hampshire will provide some momentum for him.
